I told the daycare parents that my job has been a pro athlete and then realized I had to delete all TikToks and many of the cringiest Instagram reels. Youâ€™d have thought that professional networking would have been the impetus to do this, but I am way more concerned about the other parents ğŸ¤£

I have this theory that I would be a very productive member of a more primitive societyâ€¦ I have good endurance and power â€¦solid through pregnancy and childbirth â€¦good eyesight, good dental. But then as soon as I get a virus it all falls apart. Might as well throw me to the wolves ğŸ™ƒ

So fun! Even if I felt like I havenâ€™t run in two weeks ğŸ˜. Shout out to my guys running near me who got to listen to the weird lip trills I do to relax mid race. Iâ€™d love to get some sustained training here, but Iâ€™ll take randomly showing up to local road races for now.

Nothing like lining up at a start line and realizing you are the only woman there. This was a great low-key event, with a lot of fun Christmas spirit in the fieldhouse. And with that Iâ€™ve run ten races for the year! I got weirdly sentimental driving up to the start. Iâ€™m just very grateful for all the people and experiences running has brought to my life. And while I was hoping to have a road racing renaissance in 2025, itâ€™s becoming clear that real training is not in the cards for now. I am in a cycle where Iâ€™ll go for a run and itâ€™s everything I love, but then Iâ€™ll be laid out for a day or two with this really intense fatigue response. Which is no fun. If I still wanted all my eggs in the pro-running basket, Iâ€™d do the testing and see doctors; but I kind of want to just ignore the problem and see if it goes away ğŸ¥¶. Sooâ€¦ hopefully the coming months include good running with friends as I can handle. Iâ€™d still love to train for a longer race, but weâ€™ll cross that bridge when we get there. Itâ€™s a marathon not a sprint ğŸ™ƒ

Last long run before Valencia marathon

Hereâ€™s a lil race recap for my loyal Strava followers. I got out well and established good position. After about 5.5k my pace group(2:10) combined with the 2:08 group so we were running faster than prescribed, but I was feeling strong and fueling well. I decided to let the main group go a tad and ran conservatively miles 6-12, but I decided to try and catch the main group and left my smaller group miles 12-16. I went through halfway in 1:04:40 which is right where I wanted to be. I was passing people and feeling good until all of the sudden at mile 18, both of my hamstrings cramped and I stumbled to almost a walk. I backed off the pace a tad and really tried to get everything out of my bottles because every time I pressed on the gas and tried to run pace my hamstrings would tighten. Miles 19-21.7 I couldnâ€™t get my hamstrings to stop cramping and was ebbing between 5:20-5:00/mi until both my hamstrings cramped, wouldnâ€™t release, and I collapsed. I realized my race was over. I am frustrated because aerobically I was feeling great. I put a lot into this build and am definitely heartbroken, but overall this was a good learning experience and I know that I will be stronger next time. Thank you everyone for the love and supportğŸ¤™
